To find the regions of the interest, I will do clustering using the module sklearn.cluster. K-Means clustering will be used with the num_of_clusters parameter which I set to 3.

In [5]:
# number of clusters
num_of_clusters = 3
kmeans = cluster.KMeans(n_clusters=num_of_clusters)
print(kmeans)

KMeans(n_clusters=3)

To fit the model, I should preprocess the data such that coordinates matrix will contain x and y coordinates. Moreover NaN values will be dropped.

In [6]:
# coordinates matrix
coordinates = shape[['X','Y']]
#dropping nan values
coordinates = coordinates.dropna()
print(coordinates)

Now, let us fit the model with coordinates and visualize the output :

In [7]:
# fit the model
model = kmeans.fit(coordinates)
# predict the result
clusters = model.predict(coordinates)
# scatter plot predicted result
plt.scatter(coordinates['X'],coordinates['Y'],c=clusters)
# red dots represent cluster centers
center_of_clusters = model.cluster_centers_
plt.scatter(center_of_clusters[:,0],center_of_clusters[:,1],c='red')
plt.title("Clustering Result")
Out[7]:

Now select the polygons corresponding to the clusters (0,1,2) to crop the shape file acccordingly :

In [8]:
# dictionary holding polygons for corresponding cluster
cluster_polygons={}
for i in range(num_of_clusters):
    cluster_polygons[i]=[]
for i in zip(clusters,shape['geometry']):
    cluster_polygons[i[0]].append(i[1])

Just before doing cropping, let us open and visualize the raster file :

In [9]:

Finally, let us crop the respective region of the interest and corresponding raster file part for each cluster.

In [10]:
for i in cluster_polygons.keys():
    # output file name as mentioned in the pdf
    out_file_name = "cropped_other_name_ROI_"+str(i)+".shp"
    out_file = gpd.GeoDataFrame(geometry=cluster_polygons[i])
    # plot of the cropped part
    out_file.plot()
    plt.title(out_file_name)
    # write output file
    out_file.to_file(out_file_name)
    # cropping corresponding part of raster file
    out_image,out_transform = rasterio.mask.mask(raster,cluster_polygons[i],crop=True)
    out_meta = raster.meta
    out_meta.update({
        "height":out_image.shape[1],
        "width":out_image.shape[2],
        "transform":out_transform})
    # output raster file name as mentioned in the pdf
    out_raster_name = "cropped_other_name_ROI_"+str(i)+".tif"
    # writing the cropped raster file part
    with rasterio.open(out_raster_name,"w",**out_meta) as raster_out:
        raster_out.write(out_image)

Finally, we can see visualize the cropped raster files as well.
